{{Infobox film | name = Roma come Chicago | image = Roma come Chicago.jpg | alt = | caption = | native_name = <!-- {{Infobox name module|language|title}} or {{Infobox name module|title}} --> | director = [[Alberto De Martino]] | producer = [[Dino de Laurentiis]]{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} | writer = | screenplay = {{plainlist|*Giacinto Ciaccio *Massimo D'Avack *[[Carlo Romano]] *[[Dino Maiuri]] *Massimo De Rita *Alberto De Martino *[[Fabio Carpi]] *[[Lianella Carell]] *[[Piero Tellini]]{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}}}} | story = {{plainlist|*Giacinto Ciaccio *Massimo D'Avack *Carlo Romano{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}}}} | based_on = <!-- {{Based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} --> | starring = {{plainlist|* [[John Cassavetes]] * [[Gabriele Ferzetti]] * [[Anita Sanders]] * [[Nikos Kourkoulos]]}} | narrator = | music = {{plainlist|*[[Ennio Morricone]] *[[Bruno Nicolai]]}} | cinematography = [[Aldo Tonti]]{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} | editing = [[Otello Colangeli]]{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} | studio = [[Dino de Laurentiis Cinematografica]]{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} | distributor = [[Paramount Pictures]] | released = {{Film date|df=yes|1968|11|20|Italy}} | runtime = 104 minutes{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} | country = Italy{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} | language = | budget = | gross = ₤320.84 million }}
'''''Roma come Chicago''''' (literally "Rome like Chicago") is a 1968 Italian [[crime film]] directed by [[Alberto De Martino]]. It stars actor [[Gabriele Ferzetti]].
==Cast== * [[John Cassavetes]] as Mario Corda * [[Gabriele Ferzetti]] as Commissioner * [[Anita Sanders]] as Lea Corda * [[Nikos Kourkoulos]] as Enrico * [[Riccardo Cucciolla]] as Vice-Commissioner Pascuttini * [[Luigi Pistilli]] as Colangeli * [[Osvaldo Ruggieri]] as Inspector Sernesi * [[Guido Lollobrigida]] as Angelo Scotese * [[Piero Morgia]] as Carlo Taddei
==Production== Among the films crew is cinematographer [[Aldo Tonto]] who had worked with [[Federico Fellini]] and [[Roberto Rossellini]].{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=15}} The score was composed by [[Ennio Morricone]] and [[Bruno Nicolai]].{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=15}} Morricone and Nicolai's score was re-worked music from the 1968 TV show ''[[Musica da sera]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=15}} Alberto De Martino spoke about working with [[John Cassavetes]], stating that he was "the most difficult actor I have ever worked with. When we first met, his wife [[Gena Rowlands]] came too. He introduced me to her as "the most intelligent director in Europe" which she responded with "Give him time!"{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=15}} Both De Martino and Cassavetes argued on the set but according to De Martino, the two ended production on good terms.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=15}}
''Roma come Chicago'' was shot at De Laurentiis studios and on location in Rome.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} Director [[Alberto De Martino]] discussed the films location as an "Americanized Rome".{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=15}}
==Release== ''Roma come Chicago'' was released in Italy on 20 November 1968 where it was distributed by Paramount – De Laurentiis.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} It grossed a total of 320.84 million [[Italian lira|lira]] on its theatrical run in Italy.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}} As of 2013, the film has not been released on home video.{{sfn|Curti|2013|p=14}}
==Reception== A review in the ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' stated that the film was a "fairly literal imitation of the American location thrillers of the Foties and Fifties made by Hathaway, Siodmak and others, except that it is a little more calculated in its violence."<ref name="mfb">{{cite magazine|title=Roma come Chicago (Bandits in Rome)|magazine=[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]|pages=58|volume=37|issue=434|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|date=March 1970}}</ref>
